            <fr:title text="KL divergence is jointly convex">KL divergence is jointly convex</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The <fr:link href="/000W/" title="Kullback-Liebler Divergence" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/000W/" display-uri="000W" type="local">KL divergence</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P\,\|\,Q)]]></fr:tex> is convex in the pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(P,Q)]]></fr:tex> jointly: for any two pairs and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda \in [0,1]]]></fr:tex>,
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[D_{\mathrm {KL}}\left (\lambda  P_1+(1-\lambda )P_2\ \|\ \lambda  Q_1+(1-\lambda )Q_2\right )\ \leq \ \lambda  D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P_1\|Q_1)+(1-\lambda )D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P_2\|Q_2).]]></fr:tex></html:p>
            <html:p>This drops out of the <fr:link href="/004F/" title="Log-Sum Inequality" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/004F/" display-uri="004F" type="local">Log-Sum Inequality</fr:link> applied termwise. Joint convexity is the strong statement: it immediately gives <html:em>individual</html:em> convexity in either argument (fix the other and set the two copies equal), and — via <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P\|U)=\log |\mathcal {X}|-H(P)]]></fr:tex> against the fixed uniform law — it makes <fr:link href="/TVGU/" title="Entropy is concave" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/TVGU/" display-uri="TVGU" type="local">Entropy is concave</fr:link> a corollary.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
